    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-07-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-07-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="829"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d829">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">839.00/3432</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Dominican Republic</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cabot</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santo Domingo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-07-26">July 26,
                            1930</date>.<lb/>[Received August 5.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 140</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that the last week has
                    been characterized by no salient events and that marking time seems to be the
                    order until August 16.</p>
                <p>Following the receipt of the Department’s telegram No. 31 of July 22—1 P.M., I
                    immediately discussed with Trujillo the most appropriate use which could be made
                    of the information that the American Government would recognize him and would
                    appoint Mr. Curtis special representative for the inaugural ceremonies. Both of
                    us deeming it advisable that the news be published immediately, I gave the
                    information respecting the forthcoming appointment of Mr. Curtis to the press,
                    and pointed out that this indicated the intention of the American Government to
                    recognize Trujillo.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">John M. Cabot</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
